Introduction

Context: We are working with the hotel_booking.csv dataset to better understand hotel bookings and cancellations. This dataset includes information about: dates, demographics, customer types, reservation details, cancellations, etc.

Audience: Hotel managers who are worried about hotel cancellations

Key Question: What is the root cause of cancellations and how can we mitigate this issue?

Are Cancellations a Problem?

In order to understand if cancellations are a real problem, we must explore our data! We will analyze the number of cancellations and proportion of cancellations over time and then figure out how much this is affecting our revenue

Are we losing money because of the cancellations?

table_mean_adr_canceled <- tapply(hotel$adr, hotel$is_canceled, mean, na.rm = TRUE)
df <- as.data.frame(table_mean_adr_canceled)
colnames(df) <- c("Mean ADR")
df$`Mean ADR` <- as.numeric(as.character(df$`Mean ADR`))
df$`Mean ADR` <- round(df$`Mean ADR`, 2)
df
##   Mean ADR
## 0    99.99
## 1   104.96

The table above shows the mean ADR for if the reservation was not cancelled and cancelled. As we can discern, the mean ADR is 5 dollars higher for cancelled reservations. Although this may not constitute a large difference, if extrapolated to the entire data set of almost 120,000 reservations, a large amount of money is lost. Namely, if we multiply the mean ADR by the total number of cancellations:

mean_adr_per_year <- aggregate(adr ~ arrival_date_year + is_canceled, data = hotel, mean)
graph <- ggplot(data = as.data.frame(mean_adr_per_year), aes(x=arrival_date_year, y = adr, color = is_canceled)) + geom_point(size = 6) + ggtitle("Mean ADR per Arrival Year") + labs(x = "Arrival Year", y="Mean ADR", caption=("As the year increases, the mean ADR for cancellations increases.")) + theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5), plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

# There is greater lead time in the middle of the year (summer)

LT Prop Table 1 and the above pie charts show that there is a very obvious relationship between lead time and cancellation. The further in advanced a person books, the more likely that they canceled. Of all the people who booked in the “Highest Lead Time” bucket, 55.3% ended up canceling. This is vastly different from people in the “Lowest Lead Time” bucket, where only 14% canceled. We also separated people who booked on the same day, and found that 6.8% of people canceled. This was surprising to the team because although 6.8% is relatively low, we did not expect people to change their minds so quickly.

sum(hotel$has_agent == 1 & hotel$is_canceled == 1)/sum(hotel$has_agent == 1)
## [1] 0.3900437

From the graph above, more than 39% of people who have an agent canceled their reservation compared to only 24.7% in the people who does not have an agent. This suggests that people who have an agent have more tendency to cancel their reservations compared to the ones who does not have any agent.

Solutions to the Cancellation Problem

Solution for Previous Cancellations Problem

The main reason that cancellations are a problem is because if the hotel is at capacity, or if the most profitable rooms have been booked, then you are missing out on lost revenue from the customers that would have booked and not cancelled. One solution to this problem would be to force those that have cancelled before to put down a deposit when they reserve in order to mitigate any losses that may occur from the lost revenue of other potential customers. Another solution is to reserve rooms for customers that have not cancelled in the past. You would apply Newsvendor Problem solving logic to determine the number of rooms that you leave reserved.

Analysis of Special Requests Indicators

From our analysis, we view that those who have contacted the hotel for special requests are much less likely to cancel their reservation than a client who has not made any special requests. The hotel should take note of this whenever someone makes a request. However, correlation is not causation and it is not evident whether people decide they are not canceling before they make special requests or if they do not cancel because they have made those requests.

Lead Time Analysis

In our lead time analysis, there was a clear relationship between how far in advance a person booked and whether they cancelled their reservation or not. The trend showed that the further in advance that someone booked, the more likely they were to cancel their reservation. This is a difficult problem to have because for hotels reservations are beneficial for planning and gives the hotels a safeguard against the variance in room demand within any given week.
